text: Cite this: DOI: 10.1039/c9md00066f Received 2nd February 2019, Accepted 5th August 2019 Bacterial aromatic polyketides belong to the most important class of natural products,1 since clinically used antibiotics and anticancer drugs, tetracyclines and the anthracyclines, belong to this very distinct family. The biosynthetic machinery, which is responsible for their assembly, is called type II polyketide synthase (PKS), along with several post-PKS tailoring enzymes. Genome mining re- vealed that type II PKS clusters are relatively rare and occur in as few as 8% of actinobacterial genomes.2 However, type II PKS were historically among the first to be investigated, spe- cifically actinorhodin, tetracenomycin C, doxorubicin, and tetracycline.3–8 The pioneer work of Chaitan Khosla and C. Richard Hutchinson revealed many important principles re- garding type II PKSs, particularly the fact that a cluster of a minimum of three enzymes, the ketosynthase KSα, a chain- length factor (CLF, or KSβ), and the acyl carrier protein ACP, together called the minimal PKS, is necessary to produce any- thing at all.6,7,9–11 It was also recognized that this minimal complex of enzymes is surrounded by associated enzymes, such as ketoreductases, cyclases, and aromatases, which form a complex steering the formation of an initial framework, like the isochromanequinones or the differently cyclized tetra- cyclic frameworks of the anthraquinones, tetracenomycins or angucyclines.5,6,9,12 Khosla and co-workers showed that recombining elements of the PKS complex from various path- ways could lead to novel molecular frameworks, a technique later called combinatorial biosynthesis.9,11,13–15 Department of Pharmaceutical Sciences, College of Pharmacy, University of Kentucky, 789 S. Post-PKS enzyme complexes Redding Gober, Ryan Wheeler and Jürgen Rohr Natural products are produced by bacteria, plants, and fungi and have yielded some of the most clinically active and widely used drugs available. Several of the natural products that are produced by type II PKSs have novel scaffolds or unique rearrangements that are, in large part, due to the post PKS enzymes. Pro- tein–protein interactions between post-PKS tailoring enzymes hamper the use of combinatorial biosynthe- sis in the development of novel natural product-derived drugs. Several co-dependent post-PKS enzymes have been characterized in nature, but their significance in regards to complex formation and co- dependence has been largely overlooked. Here, we report an in-depth analysis of two such post-PKS path- ways, gilvocarcin and mithramycin, for which indications exist to postulate multienzyme complexes to fa- cilitate substrate protection and channeling. Post-PKS tailoring enzymes were envisioned as stand- alone enzymes (Fig. 1), which add functional groups, such as hydroxyl or amino groups, halogens, or more sophisticated decorations, such as glycosidic residues. While it was recog- nized that polyketide framework rearranging oxygenases and glycosyltransferases were important to create or add struc- tural features that were essential or even key to the biological activities of the biosynthetic end products, these post-PKS Fig. 1 Typically envisioned, but here simplified biosynthetic pathway of a bacterial aromatic polyketide, doxorubicin, consisting of a type II PKS complex and a group of unattached, standalone post-PKS tailoring enzymes.16 Not shown are, for example, later occurring oxygenase (OX) catalyzed steps. The pivotal glycosyltransferase (GT) catalyzed steps typically occur late in such pathways.16

tailoring enzymes were less researched for a number of years.9,11,16 However, these enzymes eventually played an im- portant role in attempts to create new natural product deriva- tives through combinatorial biosynthesis or pathway engi- neering, the latter term better distinguishing these strategies through from the rearrangement and combination of PKS encoding genes.13,17 Besides some moderate successes, combinatorial biosynthe- sis and/or pathway engineering failed to hold its promises, namely significantly enriching the armamentarium against bacteria and cancers through the generation of new, clinically useful drugs.17–19 Why did these initially euphorically embraced techniques of the genetic era of biosynthetic investigations fail? We try to provide an answer by summarizing the present knowl- edge of two typical pathways of type II PKS encoded bacte- rial polyketide metabolite families, the gilvocarcins (Fig. 2) (Fig. 10), which are post-PKS and the mithramycins Fig. 2 Examples of members of the gilvocarcin type family of anticancer drugs (panel A, right), the gilvocarcin (gil), ravidomycin (rav) and chrysomycin (chry) gene clusters in comparison, (panel A, left), a cartoon of the mode-of-action (panel B) and a producing strain gilvocarcin, Strep- tomyces griseoflavus (panel C).24,28 Note that the R and M activities are encoded by a single gene in the rav and chry gene clusters, and the co- location of the MT, OII, R- and M genes in all three clusters. Both of these natural product families are deco- rated with essential saccharidal moieties and possess oxida- tively rearranged skeletons.12 The absence of several inter- mediates, co-localization of several post-PKS enzymes, and inactivity of specific enzymes in the absence of other en- zymes, among other evidence points towards interactions of some kind occurring between these post-PKS enzymes. Are these interactions directed by chaperone proteins or aided by scaffold proteins? Could they be occurring because of the formation of microcompartments or due to a yet-to-be- discovered sequential substrate transfer mechanism? The gilvocarcin family of anticancer natural products consist of roughly a dozen compounds distinct in their benzo[d] naphthopyranone chromophore and a variable sugar moiety (D-fucose, D-ravidosamine, L-rhamnose, D-virenose, etc.), which is typically C-glycosidically bound to the 4-position of the tetra- cyclic dibenzo[c,h]chromenone chromophore (see Fig. 2 for examples).18,21,24–28 In the 8-position a small side chain is at- tached (methyl, ethyl, vinyl or hydroxyethyl), vinyl being the most favorable, since it can directly interact with thymine resi- dues of DNA through a light-catalyzed [2 + 2]-photocyclization reaction.29–32 All chirality of these molecules lie in the sugar residue, which presumably interacts with histone H3, thereby crosslinking the histone and DNA which ultimately prevents transcription and freezes the nucleosome preventing replica- tion.30 This crosslinking interaction is the most likely mode-of- action of this class of anticancer drugs (Fig. 2).30 The light re- action can provide selectivity, if suitable light sources (e.g., through capillaries) are brought to the tumor site.30 This journal is © The Royal Society of Chemistry 2019

Early on it was shown with incorporation experiments using isotope-labeled precursors that the biosynthesis of the gilvocarcin type molecules emerges through an angucyclin- This journal is © The Royal Society of Chemistry 2019 one (benz[a]anthracenone) intermediate, which is oxidatively rearranged containing chromophore.24,26,33–37 The C5–C6 bond of the angucyclinone intermediate is cleaved, and C-6 is lost by decarboxylation during this process (Fig. 3).37 After cloning the gilvocarcin gene cluster (Fig. 2 and 4) gene inactivation experiments were performed that should re- veal which of the five potential oxygenases or oxidoreductases (GilOI–OIV, GilR) of the cluster was responsible for the oxida- tive cleavage reaction.21,23,25,38,39 However, the results were ambiguous. Three of the resulting gene deletion mutants ac- cumulated angucyclinones, i.e. were either partaking in or preparing the oxidative cleavage step, namely GilOI-, GilOII-, and GilOIV-minus mutants (Fig. 4).23,26,37 These results were complicated through the fact that several of these accumu- lated than shunt intermediates.37

The exact sequence of biosynthetic events and the roles of all the Gil-oxygenases OI–OIV and of oxidoreductase GilR could only be deciphered after reconstitution of the model compound defuco-gilvocarcin M with a mixture of enzymes from various related pathways.39 This enzyme mixture could further be investigated by plug-and-play variants of the en- zyme mixtures and by investigations of single enzymes, and yielded many surprises (Fig. 5): GilOIV acts first, but not as an oxygenase and instead as a PKS release enzyme, and GilOI has two activities, and catalyzes both, a 4a,12b-dehydration and 12-hydroxylation.23,37,39 A P450 enzyme, GilOIII, is re- sponsible for forming the 8-vinyl group from an ethyl group.21 Though the direct dehydrogenation mechanism for the GilOIII oxidation step is more likely due to the absence of a hydroxylated intermediate, indirect mechanism consisting of hydroxylation followed by dehydration remains a possibility.21,40 Most intriguing, GilOII turned out to be the C–C-bond cleaving enzyme.26,39 It catalyzes two consecutive oxidation steps, (i) a 5-hydroxylation, and (ii) Baeyer–Villiger oxidation of the 6-keto group.23 It is a twice acting FADH- dependent monooxygenase, although its amino acid se- quence does not reveal an FAD binding site (Fig. 6).24

The studies also showed that the GilOII product is unsta- ble and needs to be picked up immediately by the enzymes GilMT and GilM, which act after GilOII.26,39 Another surprise was that GilM, while the original sequencing (2003) revealed no match to known enzymes, is a bifunctional enzyme acting as both a quinone reductase and O-methyltransferase.22 The amino acid sequence of GilM now (in 2019) indicates a SAM binding site, but no FAD binding site, albeit both co-factors are needed as our investigations proved (Fig. 7).24 It turned out that GilM shares an FAD-cofactor with the oxidoreductase GilR, which acts as the last enzyme of the pathway, and cata- lyzes a dehydrogenation of a lactol (cyclic hemiacetal) to a lactone moiety.22 The comparison of the gilvocarcin with the chrysomycin and ravidomycin gene clusters, both of which are members the gilvocarcin-type family of anticancer antibiotics, of showed that the latter two encode both the R and M activities by one gene, while these genes are separated in the gil cluster (Fig. 2).20,23,24,41 The three gene clusters have in common that the MT, OII, R and M genes are always co-located, facili-

tating the expression of each of these enzymes and poten- tially leading to an enzyme complex that catalyzes consecu- tive reactions involving reactive, thus unstable, intermediates (here the aldehyde function and the hydroquinone spontane- ously re-oxidizes to the quinone in aerobic conditions).22,24 While an enzyme complex encoded by the MT, OII, R, and M genes is hypothetical, the co-localization and unstable inter- mediates provide indications of such a complex. GilR is a vanillyl-alcohol oxidase type flavoprotein, with a doubly cova- lently linked FAD co-factor.20,41 The crystal structure shows the substrate sandwiched between the co-factor and the cata- lytically important tyrosines 139, 448 and 445 (Fig. 8).41 The conditions used to obtain the crystal structure of GilR resulted in the formation of a dimer.41 Additional evidence for a GilR dimer was found by light scattering and analytical ultracentrifugation, although it is not confirmed whether a dimeric form exists in vivo.41 However even in the dimeric form GilR's FAD co-factor remains accessible for GilM, so that in a hypothetical complex dimeric GilR might be paired with either two monomeric GilM enzymes or with a GilM di- mer. The roles of GilM, GilGT, and GilR are further described in Fig. 7. The utilization and regeneration of FAD and FADH2 between GilM–GilR and the unstable intermediates produced by GilOII and GilM suggests these enzymes form larger post- PKS-enzyme complexes.14,20 Other possible explanations in- volve yet-to-be-discovered sequential transfer mechanisms, or the requirement of chaperone or cell structure assistance. In summary, although no direct biophysical evidence ex- ists so far, indirect evidence suggests that the gilvocarcin bio- synthetic pathway involves transient post-PKS enzyme com- plexes, (i) up to the key C–C bond cleavage, and (ii) from the C–C bond cleavage by GilOII on, including all enzymes that catalyze follow-up reactions that stabilize or defuse reactive intermediates and those finishing the biosynthesis.

The mithramycin pathway can be divided in PKS and post- PKS steps. The first isolable pathway intermediate, and there- demethyl- fore premithramycinone, which immediately is turned over to the more through the methyl- transferase MtmMI.42 The PKS complex of the mithramycin pathway is not well understood. For example: why is there a PKS associated ketoreductase? MtmTI does not reduce the poly-β-ketoester-turning point keto group (i.e. 9-O in the na- scent polyketide, which becomes 6-OH of the mithramycin aglycone).43 Additionally, what is the exact involvement of the oxygenase MtmOII? 1,3- Alignment dioxygenase, proposed to introduce 1′-O and 2-O of mithramycin.43,44 The post-PKS steps of the mithramycin pathway are better investigated, and can be functionally di- vided into three consecutive events, (i) the formation and at- tachment of the trisaccharide chain, (ii) the formation and attachment of the disaccharide chain, and (iii) the oxidative rearrangement and follow-up steps (Fig. 10).43 This journal is © The Royal Society of Chemistry 2019 We now suggest that all three events are catalyzed by tran- sient enzyme complexes, which consist of 5 enzymes for the trisaccharide formation and 2 enzymes for each of the follow- ing two events.45–50 The key pair of the 5-enzyme complex leading to the trisaccharide consists of the glycosyltransferase (GT) MtmGIV and the methyltransferase MtmC. While, to our knowledge, the former is the most unusual GT ever found, in that it catalyzes two non-consecutive GT steps using drasti- cally different donor- and acceptor substrates for both steps, the latter turned out to be a bifunctional enzyme catalyzing a ketoreductase (KR) and a C-methyltransfer step. In addition, MtmC and MtmGIV are interdependent.46

The interplay between MtmC and MtmGIV is shown in Fig. 11. First, MtmC acts as 4-KR, reducing the deoxysugar 4-keto-D-olivose to D-olivose, either after or immediately before MtmGIV utilizes TDP-4-keto-D-olivose (or TDP-D-olivose) to gly- cosylate 12a-OH of premithramycinone. Either way, this first combined action of yields premithramycin A1. Although the intermediate of this pro- cess, keto-olivosyl-premithramycinone, isolable, evi- dence for it exists in keto-premithramycins and keto- mithramycins isolated from block mutants, while enzyme ki- netics favor the olivosyl-transfer.46,51 Then the MtmGIII- catalyzed oliosyl-transfer and the MtmMII-catalyzed C-methyl- transfer acts on premithramycin A1, before the pair MtmC– MtmGIV catalyze a second set of collaborative steps. The two enzymes MtmGI and GII catalyze the formation and attachment of the disaccharide chain.50 Inactivation ex- periments of MtmGI- and MtmGII-yield premithramycin A3 as the main product, along with minor amounts of premithramycins A2 and A1. MtrAB, known to channel mithramycin out of argillaceus cells (Fig. 14).56 Surprisingly, the incubation of premithramycin B with both, MtmOIV and MtmW yielded not mithramycin, as expected, but iso- mithramycin (Fig. 16). Using mithramycin DK (Fig. 13) as a substrate, enzyme studies also

Fig. 16 Conversion of premithramycin with a mix of the enzymes MtmOIV and MtmW led surprisingly to iso-mithramycin, a recently discovered cryptic pathway intermediate with R-configuration at C-2 (S in mithramycin). revealed that MtmW is inactive, and only functions as a keto- reductase in the presence of MtmOIV.54 In addition, it was found that iso-mithramycin is biologically inactive.54 Thus, the pairing of MtmOIV–MtmW to a sophisticated enzyme complex fulfills three purposes, (i) protection and channeling of an unstable intermediate (mithramycin DK), (ii) further ac- tivation, and (iii) out-transport to avoid host DNA damage (Fig. 14). For the mithramycin biosynthesis, an overall picture emerges that suggests a loosely assembled structure of a PKS and three post-PKS enzyme complexes (Fig. 17). Conclusions and discussion In addition to their main metabolite, which is typically the most biologically active, many organisms produce several side and/or shunt products, for instance, Streptomyces spe- cies that produce gilvocarcin V often also yield gilvocarcin M and gilvocarcin E.13 This raises the question, given that the primary benefits of multienzyme complexes are substrate channeling and protection of labile intermediates, why inter- mediates can escape from post-PKS complexes?12,58 The an- Fig. 17 PKS and post-PKS enzyme complexes assemble and guide the progressing pathway intermediates towards the membrane channel, where the final product mithramycin is formed and out-transported. For colors symbolizing the enzymes see pervious figures. The figure- 8 loop of substrate/product flow within the trisaccharide forming 5-enzyme complex is shown as thin black line.

swer may lie in diversification. More intermediates may be analogous to gene duplication in the evolution of the chro- mosome in that more substrates are available for new or existing enzymes. A range of substrates may be a form of combinatorial biosynthesis initiated by the organism. Small concentrations of these shunt products are relatively free from selective pressure as the major product fulfills the eco- logical function of the secondary metabolite. In contrast, the mithramycin post-PKS pathway does not release intermedi- ates, suggesting a single multienzyme complex or a tightly as- sociated group of complexes. It is likely that the instability of intermediates or biosynthetic building blocks along with the last the responsible is mainly streamlining of the mithramycin post-PKS pathway. Although the hypothesis of post-PKS enzyme complexes was investigated and suggested here for only two biosynthetic pathways, there is evidence for similar post-PKS complexes in other pathways due to multifunctional and co-dependent enzymes.59–67 For instance, while no direct biophysical evi- dence a indirect glycosyltransfer complex for the saquayamycin pathway, and multiple acting glycosyltransferases were also found in the landomycin and mycinamicin pathways.59–61 A multienzyme complex involving a monooxygenase and two cyclases, from the pradimicin pathway has also been proposed.63 The en- zymes within this complex were shown to have no activity in- dependently and were only functional when in solution with the other enzymes in the complex.63 The possibility of a glycosyltransfer complex, possibly involving PdmQ or PdmS, occurring later in the pradimicin pathway remains another possibility.62,63 Multiple-acting oxygenases were found in the oviedomycin pathway, and co-dependent enzyme complexes in the tirandamycin pathway biosyntheses.64,65

PKS complexes are generally accepted in type I and type II PKSs, although in type II PKSs a direct physical interaction could only be proven for the ketosynthase/chain length factor (KS/CLF or KSα/KSβ) pair, which obviously need to interact with the acyl carrier protein (ACP), forming the so-called min- imal PKS.66,67 While this “minimal PKS” can act by itself, it does not produce correct intermediates, but always shunt products due to the unstable nature of the true intermedi- ates. ketoreductases, aromatases, etc. are required within the PKS complex.68 A This journal is © The Royal Society of Chemistry 2019 similar logic can be applied for post-PKS complexes, with intermediate instability being one important factor.12 Other factors discussed here in relation to mithramycin were channeling and host-DNA protection. However, physical in- teractions of post-PKS enzymes may be difficult to prove as many of these protein–protein interactions are short lived, and likely triggered by the channeling of products/substrates, and not strong enough for, e.g., pull down assays.
